g crises in Japan and the Eurozone. As we try to make sense of what caused these crises and how we might reduce risk factors and prevent recurrence, the fields of finance and economics have also seen vast change, as scholars and researchers have advanced their thinking to better respond to the recent crises. A momentous collection of the best recent scholarship, After the Flood illustrates both the scope of the crises' impact on our understanding of global financial markets and the innovative processes whereby scholars have adapted their research to gain a greater understanding of them. Among the contributors are José Scheinkman and Lars Peter Hansen, who bring up to date decades of collaborative research on the mechanisms that tie financial markets to the broader economy; Patrick Bolton, who argues that limiting bankers' pay may be more effective than limiting the activities they can undertake; Edward Glaeser and Bruce Sacerdote, who study the social dynamics of markets; and E. Glen Weyl, who argues that economists are influenced by the incentives their consulting opportunities create.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 4aJosé Scheinkman. 4aasset pricing. 4afinancial crisis. 4afinancial regulation. 4agreat recession. 70(DE-601)10448361X0(DE-588)4079351-5aWirtschaftstheorie2gnd 70(DE-601)1057719290(DE-588)4121078-5aCapital-Asset-Pricing-Modell2gnd 70(DE-601)1060915140(DE-588)4073788-3aKreditmarkt2gnd 70(DE-601)5872729100(DE-588)7635855-0aFinanzkrise2gnd 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aGlaeser, Edward L., eeditor.1 aSantos, Tano, eeditor.1 aWeyl, E. Glen, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226443683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/cove